APPENDIX __ TRANSCANYON WESTERN DEVELOPMENT, LLC FORMULA RATE IMPLEMENTATION PROTOCOLS The Formula Rate Template (Template) and these Formula Rate Implementation Protocols (Protocols) together comprise the filed rate (Formula Rate) of TransCanyon Western Development, LLC (TransCanyon) for transmission revenue requirement determinations. TransCanyon shall follow the instructions specified in the Formula Rate to calculate annually its net revenue requirement, as set forth at page 1, line 4 of the Template (Net Revenue Requirement). The project-specific net revenue requirements determined under the Formula Rate are up to rates, i.e., ceiling rates, and permit TransCanyon to discount the revenue requirement for a future project to the extent necessary to reflect the results of another project. In the event that TransCanyon submits a bid for a future project that contains a discounted, capped, or otherwise limited revenue requirement and that bid is selected via a competitive proceeding, TransCanyons revenue requirement for that project will be the lower of: (a) the discounted, capped, or otherwise limited revenue requirement, or (b) the actual revenue requirement produced by the Template. The Net Revenue Requirement (page 1, line 4 of the Template) shall be determined for January 1 to December 31 of a given calendar year (the Rate Year). The Formula Rate shall become effective for recovery of TransCanyons Net Revenue Requirement upon the effective date authorized by the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission (FERC or the Commission) under Section 205 of the Federal Power Act (FPA) for this Formula Rate. A chart depicting the schedule for Annual Projections, Annual Updates, and Annual Reviews of the Formula Rate can be found at the end of these Protocols. Section 1. Annual Projection 1
a. No later than September 30 preceding the first Rate Year that TransCanyon expects to recover Net Revenue Requirements under the Tariff, and each subsequent Rate Year thereafter, TransCanyon shall determine its projected Net Revenue Requirement for the upcoming Rate Year in accordance with TransCanyons Formula Rate (Annual Projection). The Annual Projection shall include the True-up Adjustment described and defined in Section 2 below, if applicable. TransCanyon shall cause an electronic version of the Annual Projection to be posted in both a Portable Document Format and fully-functioning Excel file at publicly accessible locations on TransCanyons OASIS. Such posting shall include (i) all inputs in sufficient detail to identify the components of TransCanyons projected Net Revenue Requirement, and (ii) explanations of the bases for the projections and input data. If the date for making such posting of the Annual Projection should fall on a weekend or a holiday recognized by FERC, then the posting shall be made no later than the next business day. TransCanyon shall electronically serve each Annual 1 Projection upon the Exploder List. b. Within two business days after the posting of the Annual Projection, TransCanyon shall cause to be posted on the TransCanyon website and OASIS the time, date, location, and telephonic access information for an annual stakeholder meeting (the Annual Projection Stakeholder
1 As used in these protocols, the term Exploder List shall mean: (i) the email list of TransCanyon Customers; (ii) any state regulatory agency with rate jurisdiction over TransCanyon; (iii) the service list in FERC proceeding Docket No. ER21-___-000 (except for FERC Trial Staff); and (iv) any other Interested Party, as that term is defined below in Section 1(b), that wishes to be included on the Exploder List, provided that such Interested Party requests to be placed on the Exploder List and provides an e-mail address to TransCanyon. 2
Meeting) to: (i) permit TransCanyon to explain and clarify its Annual 2 Projection; and (ii) provide Interested Parties an opportunity to seek information and clarifications from TransCanyon about the Annual Projection. TransCanyon shall also provide notice of such meeting to the Exploder List. The Annual Projection Stakeholder Meeting shall be held no less than twenty (20) business days and no more than thirty (30) business days after September 30. If requested by Interested Persons, TransCanyon will hold an additional Annual Projection Stakeholder Meeting to discuss any outstanding issues. Interested Persons requesting an additional Annual Projection Stakeholder Meeting shall provide TransCanyon with a list of all issues to be discussed at the meeting. c. To the extent that TransCanyon agrees to make changes in the Annual Projection for a given Rate Year, such revised Annual Projection shall be promptly posted at publicly accessible locations on TransCanyons OASIS, and a link to the OASIS shall be electronically served upon the Exploder List. Changes posted prior to November 30 of the preceding Rate Year, or the next business day if November 30 is not a business day, shall be reflected in the Annual Projection for the Rate Year; changes posted after that date will be reflected, as appropriate, in the True-up Adjustment for the Rate Year in the following years Annual Update.
2 For purposes of these protocols, the term Interested Party includes, but is not limited to, customers under the Formula Rate, state utility regulatory commissions, consumer advocacy agencies as applicable, and state attorneys general. 3
d. The Annual Projection, including the True-Up Adjustment, for each Rate Year shall be subject to review, challenge, true-up and refunds or surcharges with interest at the applicable FERC rate, to the extent and in the manner provided in these Protocols. Section 2. True-up Adjustment TransCanyon will calculate the amount of under- or over-collection of its actual Net Revenue Requirement during the preceding Rate Year (True-up Adjustment) after the FERC Form No. 1 data for that Rate Year has been filed with the Commission. The True-up Adjustment shall be the sum of components a and b, determined in the following manner: a. TransCanyons actual transmission revenue billed during the previous Rate Year will be compared to TransCanyons actual Net Revenue Requirement for the previous Rate Year calculated in accordance with TransCanyons Formula Rate and based upon (i) TransCanyons FERC Form No. 1 for that same Rate Year, (ii) any FERC orders specifically applicable to TransCanyons calculation of its annual revenue requirement, (iii) the books and records of TransCanyon (which shall be maintained consistent with the FERC Uniform System of Accounts (USoA)), and (iv) FERC accounting policies and practices applicable to the calculation of annual revenue requirements under formula rates, to determine any over- or under-recovery (True-up Adjustment Over/Under Recovery). TransCanyon will include a variance analysis of, at minimum, actual revenue requirement components of rate base, operating and maintenance expenses, depreciation expense, taxes, return on rate 4
base, and revenue credits as compared to the corresponding components in the projected revenue requirement that was calculated for the prior Rate Year with an explanation of material changes. b. Interest on any True-up Adjustment Over/Under Recovery of the actual Net Revenue Requirement shall be calculated in accordance with the Formula Rate true-up worksheet. Section 3. Annual Update a. On or before the June 30 following each Rate Year, TransCanyon shall calculate its actual Net Revenue Requirement and the True-up Adjustment as described in Section 2 (Annual Update) for such Rate Year, and shall cause such Annual Update to be posted, in both a Portable Document Format and fully-functioning Excel format containing the populated Template for that years update, at publicly accessible locations on TransCanyons internet website and OASIS, and electronically serve links to the website and OASIS upon the Exploder List. In addition, the Annual Update shall be submitted to the FERC as an informational filing following the conclusion of the Review Period, as that term is defined in Section 4. The informational filing must include any corrections or adjustments made during the Review Period, and must note any aspects of the formula rate or inputs that are subject to dispute. Additionally, the informational filing must include information that is reasonably necessary to determine: (1) that input data under the formula rate are properly recorded in any underlying workpapers; (2) that TransCanyon has 5
properly applied the formula rate and the procedures in the protocols; (3) the accuracy of data and the consistency with the formula rate of the actual revenue requirement and rates (including any true-up adjustment) under review; (4) the extent of accounting changes that affect formula rate inputs; and (5) the reasonableness of projected costs included in the projected capital addition expenditures. b. If the date for making the Annual Update posting should fall on a weekend or a holiday recognized by the FERC, then the posting shall be due on the next business day. c. The date on which the last of the Annual Update posting events listed in Section 3.a occursi.e., June 30 or the first business day after June 30, as specified in Section 3.b.shall be that years Publication Date. d. Within two business days after the Publication Date, TransCanyon shall cause to be posted on the TransCanyon OASIS the time, date, location, and telephonic access information for an annual stakeholder meeting (the Annual Update Stakeholder Meeting) to: (i) permit TransCanyon to explain and clarify its Annual Update; and (ii) provide Interested Parties an opportunity to seek information and clarifications from TransCanyon about the Annual Update. TransCanyon shall also provide notice of such meeting to the Exploder List. The Annual Update Stakeholder Meeting shall be held no less than twenty (20) business days and no more than thirty (30) business days after June 30. If requested by Interested Persons, TransCanyon will hold an additional Annual Update Stakeholder Meeting 6
to discuss any outstanding issues. Interested Persons requesting an additional Annual Update Stakeholder Meeting shall provide TransCanyon with a list of all issues to be discussed at the meeting. e. The Annual Update for the Rate Year: (i) Shall provide, via the Formula Rate worksheets, sufficiently detailed supporting documentation for data (and all adjustments thereto or allocations thereof) used in the Formula Rate that are not 3 stated in the FERC Form No. 1; (ii) Shall provide notice and details of any changes in TransCanyons accounting policies and practices from those in effect for the calendar year upon which the immediately preceding Annual Update was based that affect the Formula Rate or calculation of the Annual Update (Accounting Change(s)). Such notice and details shall include (i) those changes that, in TransCanyons reasonable judgment, could impact the Formula Rate or the calculations under the Formula Rate within the next three years; and (ii) any change, and the dollar value of the change, in the classification of any transmission facility that TransCanyon has made in the applicable True-Up Adjustment or Annual Update.
3 It is the intent of the Formula Rate, including the supporting explanations and allocations described therein, that each input to the Formula Rate for purposes of determining the actual Net Revenue Requirement for a given Rate Year will be either taken directly from the FERC Form No. 1 or reconcilable to the FERC Form No. 1 by the application of clearly identified and supported information. If the referenced form is superseded, the successor form(s) shall be utilized and supplemented as necessary to provide equivalent information as that provided in the superseded form. If the referenced form is discontinued, equivalent information as that provided in the discontinued form shall be utilized. 7
(iii) Shall provide interested persons information about TransCanyons implementation of the formula rate in sufficient detail and with sufficient explanation to demonstrate that each input into the formula rate is consistent with the requirements of the formula rate. (iv) Shall be subject to review and challenge in accordance with the procedures set forth in Sections 4, 5, and 6 of these Protocols; provided, however, that with respect to the prudence of any costs and expenditures included for recovery in the Annual Update, nothing in these Protocols is intended to modify the Commissions applicable precedent with respect to the burden of going forward or burden of proof under formula rates in such prudence challenges; and (v) Shall not seek to modify the Formula Rate or constitute the basis for an attempt by an Interested Person to modify the Formula Rate (i.e., any modifications to the Formula Rate will require, as applicable, an FPA Section 205 or Section 206 filing or initiation of a Section 206 investigation). f. The following Formula Rate inputs shall be stated values to be used in the Formula Rate until changed pursuant to an FPA Section 205 or 206 proceeding: (i) rate of return on common equity (ROE); (ii) Post- Employment Benefits other than Pensions pursuant to Statement of Financial Accounting Standards No. 106, Employers Accounting for 8
Postretirement Benefits Other Than Pensions (PBOP) charges identified on lines 151-188 of Attachment 2 to the Template; and (iii) the depreciation and/or amortization rates as set forth in Attachment 9 to the Template. No change may be made to the ROE, PBOP expenses, or depreciation and/or amortization rates absent a filing under Section 205 or 206 of the FPA.
g. Example Timeline for Annual Update: On or before September 30, Year 1, TransCanyon will determine the projected Net Revenue Requirement for the following Rate Year 2. TransCanyon will post the Annual Projection for the Year 2 Rate Year in accordance with Section 1 above. TransCanyon would not determine a True-up Adjustment or post an Annual Update on June 30, Year 2 if no costs have been recovered under the Formula Rate during Year 1. On or before September 30, Year 2, TransCanyon will post the Annual Projection for the Year 3 Rate Year. On or before June 30, Year 3, TransCanyon will post its first Annual Update, consisting of the True-up Adjustment for the Year 2 Rate Year determined pursuant to Section 2 above. Such True-up Adjustment would be reflected in the Annual Projection of the Net Revenue Requirement for the Year 4 Rate Year posted on or before September 30, Year 3. The Annual Update posted June 30, Year 3 would be subject to the customer review and challenge procedures described in Sections 4, 5, and 6 of these Protocols. 9
Section 4. Annual Review Procedures Each Annual Update shall be subject to the following review procedures (Annual Review Procedures): a. Interested Persons shall have up to the latest of one hundred fifty (150) calendar days after the Publication Date, thirty (30) calendar days after the receipt of all responses to timely submitted information requests (unless such period is extended with the written consent of TransCanyon), or thirty (30) calendar days after resolution of a dispute that does not result in the production of additional information (Review Period), to review the calculations and to notify TransCanyon in writing of any specific challenges, including but not limited to challenges related to Accounting Changes, to the Annual Update (Preliminary Challenge). TransCanyon shall promptly cause to be posted all Preliminary Challenges at publicly accessible locations on TransCanyons internet website and OASIS, and links to the website and OASIS will be electronically served upon the Exploder List. TransCanyon shall respond in writing to a Preliminary Challenge within twenty (20) business days of receipt, and its response shall notify the challenging party of the extent to which TransCanyon agrees or disagrees with the challenge. If TransCanyon disagrees with the Preliminary Challenge, its response shall include supporting documentation. TransCanyon shall promptly cause to be posted responses to all Preliminary Challenges at publicly accessible locations on 10
TransCanyons internet website and OASIS, and links to the website will be electronically served upon the Exploder List. b. Interested Persons shall have up to one hundred twenty (120) calendar days after each annual Publication Date (unless such period is extended with the written consent of TransCanyon) to serve reasonable information and document requests upon TransCanyon. Information and document requests that are received shall be posted at publicly accessible locations on TransCanyons internet website and OASIS, and links to the website and OASIS will be electronically served upon the Exploder List. TransCanyon shall use best efforts to respond to information and document requests pertaining to the Annual Update within ten (10) business days of receipt of such requests. To the extent TransCanyon and any Interested Person(s) are unable to resolve disputes related to information and document requests submitted in accordance with these Annual Review Procedures, TransCanyon or any Interested Person may petition the FERC to appoint an Administrative Law Judge as a discovery master to resolve the discovery dispute(s) in accordance with these Protocols and consistent with the FERCs discovery rules. c. Interested Persons shall have up to 30 calendar days after the Review Period to file a challenge with FERC (Formal Challenge), unless such period is extended with the written consent of TransCanyon. d. Information and document requests, Preliminary Challenges, and Formal Challenges, shall be limited to what is necessary to determine: (1) the 11
extent, effect, or impact of an accounting change; (2) whether the Annual True-Up fails to include data properly recorded in accordance with the protocols; (3) the proper application of the formula rate and procedures in the protocols; (4) the accuracy of data and consistency with the formula rate of the changes shown in the annual update; (5) the prudence of the actual costs and expenditures; (6) the effect of any change to the underlying USofA or applicable form; and (7) any other information that may reasonably have substantive effect on the calculation of the charge pursuant to the formula. e. If a change made by TransCanyon to its accounting policies, practices or procedures, or the application of the Formula Rate, is found by the FERC to be unjust, unreasonable, and/or unduly discriminatory or preferential, then the calculation of the charges to be assessed during the Rate Year then under review, and the charges to be assessed during any subsequent Rate Years, including any True-up Adjustments, shall not include such change, but shall include any remedy that may be prescribed by FERC in the exercise of its discretion as of the effective date of such remedy, to ensure that the Formula Rate continues to operate in a manner that is just, reasonable, and not unduly discriminatory or preferential. Section 5. Resolution of Challenges a. Interested Persons may file a Preliminary Challenge to the Annual Update, or a Formal Challenge with the FERC, which shall be served on TransCanyon by electronic service on the date of such filing. All 12
information and correspondence produced by TransCanyon pursuant to these Protocols may be included in any Formal Challenge or other FERC proceeding relating to the Formula Rate so long as it is filed as Privileged or Critical Energy Infrastructure Information when applicable. Interested Persons may challenge, through a Formal Challenge, the justness and reasonableness of TransCanyons implementation of the Formula Rate with respect to any issues permitted to be raised in a Preliminary Challenge, as outlined in Section 4, above. Formal Challenges must be filed in the same docket as the informational filings made pursuant to these protocols. b. Failure to raise an issue in a Preliminary Challenge shall not bar an Interested Person from raising that issue in a Formal Challenge. Likewise, failure to make a Preliminary Challenge shall not bar an Interested Person from making a subsequent Preliminary Challenge related to a subsequent Annual Update to the extent the issue affects the subsequent Annual Update. c. Any response by TransCanyon to a Formal Challenge must be submitted to the FERC within thirty (30) calendar days of the date of the filing of the Formal Challenge, and shall be served on the filing party or parties and the Exploder List by electronic service on the date of such filing. d. In any proceeding concerning a given years Annual Update (including corrections) or Accounting Change(s), TransCanyon shall bear the burden, consistent with section 205 of the FPA, of proving the justness and 13
reasonableness of the rate resulting from its application of the Formula Rate by demonstrating: (i) that it has reasonably and accurately calculated the Annual Update by properly and reasonably applying the Formula Rate and the procedures in these Protocols; (ii) that is has reasonably adopted and applied any Accounting Changes and such Accounting Changes are consistent with the USofA, unless otherwise approved by FERC; (iii) the costs to be recovered through TransCanyons Formula Rate have been accurately stated, properly recorded and accounted for pursuant to applicable FERC accounting practices and procedures and the USofA, unless otherwise approved by FERC; (iv) its projections have been reasonably made; (v) its calculation methodologies are consistent with the Formula Rate; and (vi) unless the Accounting Change is in accordance with an order from FERC or another regulatory agency, that the application of the Formula Rate Template and Protocols in conjunction with the Accounting Change does not fundamentally change the ratemaking treatment of the underlying accounting item. e. Except as specifically provided herein, nothing herein shall be deemed to limit in any way the right of TransCanyon to file unilaterally, pursuant to Section 205 of the FPA and the regulations thereunder, an application seeking changes to the Formula Rate or to any of the stated value inputs requiring a Section 205 filing under these Protocols, or the right of any other party or the Commission to seek such changes pursuant to Section 206 of the FPA and the regulations thereunder. All parties reserve the 14
right to contest such filing(s) and are not precluded from raising issues related to or that seek to change any other aspect of the Formula. Section 6. Single Issue Filings. a. TransCanyon may make limited filings for issues identified below. All parties reserve the right to contest such filing(s). b. TransCanyon may, at its discretion and at a time of its choosing, make limited, single issue filings pursuant to Section 205: (i) to modify the stated values in the Formula Rate for amortization and depreciation rates; (ii) to make ministerial changes to the Template to correct obvious errors, omissions, or changes in circumstance, such as a change in legal name of TransCanyon or changes to the FERC Form No. 1 that affect cell references in the Template or to delete aspects of the Formula Rate that are no longer relevant or necessary to include in the Formula Rate; (iii) to seek recovery of abandoned plant or a regulatory asset; (iv) to seek recovery of CWIP in rate base or change the amount of CWIP in rate base for one or more projects for which the CWIP in rate base incentive has already been granted by the FERC; (v) to revise the name of any affiliate listed on Attachment 2, Calculation of PBOP Expenses, to the extent the legal name of such affiliate is changed; 15
(vi) to increase the stated value for Total PBOP expenses on Attachment 2 of the Template for an affiliate if the Cost per labor dollar of PBOP expenses for that affiliate, as reflected in the Annual Update, is lower by 20% or more using the stated value for Total PBOP expenses than using the PBOP expenses for that affiliate indicated in the actuarial report for the calendar year corresponding to the Annual Update; and (vii) to modify the manner in which Accumulated Deferred Income Tax (ADIT) balances are calculated in the event that (i) FERC or an appellate court of competent jurisdiction issues an order reversing or modifying FERCs holding in Midcontinent Independent System Operator, Inc., 153 FERC ¶ 61,371 (2015), that the proration calculation set forth in Section 1.167-(1)(h)(6)(ii) of the Treasury regulations does not apply to any portion of the calculation of a utilitys annual true-up, (ii) the Internal Revenue Service (IRS) issues a Private Letter Ruling (PLR) to TransCanyon (or one of its affiliates if TransCanyon seeks such PLR in conjunction with its affiliate(s)) indicating that the manner in which ADIT balances are calculated is not in compliance with the IRSs normalization rules, or (iii) the IRS issues any ruling of general applicability (e.g., Revenue Ruling, Revenue Procedure, Notice, etc.), or Treasury issues further regulations, clarifying how the IRS interprets its Code and/or the Treasury regulations that indicates that the manner 16
in which ADIT balances are calculated is not in compliance with the IRSs normalization rules. c. TransCanyon must make a limited, single issue filing pursuant to Section 205: (i) to decrease the stated value for Total PBOP expenses on Attachment 2 of the Template for an affiliate if the Cost per labor dollar of PBOP expenses for that affiliate, as reflected in the Annual Update, is higher by 20% or more using the stated value for Total PBOP expenses than using the PBOP expense for that affiliate indicated in the actuarial report for the calendar year corresponding to the Annual Update; and (ii) to adopt a stated PBOP expense for any affiliated employees whose PBOP expenses are not captured by one of the actuarial reports described in Attachment 2. d. The limited single issue filings described in Sections 6.b(i), 6.b(ii), 6.b(iii), 6.b(iv), 6.b(v), 6.b(vi), and 6.b(vii) may also include non-material changes to the formula necessary to implement the modifications, such as adding or removing lines on supporting schedules to accommodate new line items. e. Limited single issue filings made pursuant to Section 6.b(vi) or Section 6.c(i) shall seek an effective date of January 1 in the year following the posting of the Annual Update in which the 20% or greater differential is 17
identified. Section 7. Changes to Annual Updates If TransCanyon determines or concedes that corrections to the Annual Update are required, whether under Sections 4 or 5 of these Protocols, including but not limited to those requiring corrections to its FERC Form No. 1, or input data used for a Rate Year that would have affected the Annual Update for that Rate Year, TransCanyon shall promptly notify the Exploder List, file a correction to the Annual Update with the FERC as an amended informational filing, and cause such information to be posted at publicly accessible locations on TransCanyons internet website and OASIS. Such corrections shall be subject to review at the time they are made and shall be reflected in the next Annual Update, with interest. A corrected posting shall reset the deadlines under Section 4 and 5 of the Protocols for Interested Person review and the revised dates shall run from the posting date(s) for each of the corrections. The scope of review applicable during the portion of the deadlines extended beyond the original deadlines shall be limited to the aspects of the Formula Rate affected by the corrections. Interest on any over- or under-recovery due to corrections for preceding True-up Adjustments shall be calculated monthly on such over- or under-recovery from January 1 of the corrected Rate Year through December 31 of the Rate Year in which such over- or under-recovery is reflected (Correction Period). The applicable monthly interest rates for the Correction Period for an under-recovery or over-recovery shall be the average monthly interest rate determined in accordance 18 C.F.R § 35.19a for the period from the beginning of the Correction Period through December 31 of the Rate Year immediately preceding the Rate Year in which such under-recovery is reflected. There is no time limit with respect to TransCanyons obligation or right to correct an error in the implementation of the formula rate. Nothing in this section is intended to limit FERCs 18
discretion to direct a correction to an Annual Update, or the rights of Interested Persons to seek a correction to the Formula Rate pursuant to Section 206 of the FPA.
